metadata.name: Electric Hope #82
metadata.description:
Perceived as fabric of dark and vivid thoughts, hope is always there. Sparse layers of squares form an intricate colorful lattice reflecting mixed feelings of hopelessness and hopefulness, doubt and optimism.

Press S to save. To download in custom size (ex. 2000px width), add &size=2000 to url, reload and press S.

Inspired by CMYK halftone printing patterns

Made with p5js especially for #fxhashturnsone event. 50% of primary sales will be donated to Processing Foundation

metadata.name: Journeys #4
metadata.description:
As #fxhashturnsone, it seemed apt to release one of my old WIPs, Journeys, to showcase my own journey in the creative coding space. The piece tries to recreate subway maps in a generative fashion, and is meant to reflect the journeys of people as they move and interact with each other. Some journey alongside each other before branching off, while others only meet at the end of their journeys. Even more will never meet at all.   

SAs #fxhashturnsone, it seemed apt to release one of my old WIPs, Journeys, to showcase my own journey in the creative coding space. The piece tries to recreate subway maps in a generative fashion, and is meant to reflect the journeys of people as they move and interact with each other. Some journey alongside each other before branching off, while others only meet at the end of their journeys. Even more will never meet at all.   

Several flow fields randomly determine the flow of each line, while attractors cause lines to be naturally drawn to certain places on the map. The code checks to ensure that lines do not overlap (but they can intersect!) and ensures a minimum distance between adjacent lines. Several code chunks are referenced in the comments which calculate intersections between points / lines.

THIS CODE IS VERY MUCH RAW AND UNFINISHED! It reflects my own growth in the space, where I started out, and where I'm heading towards. Happy birthday fxHash! I hope everyone finds their own Journey out there.

metadata.name: Asterium #275
metadata.description:
Asterium is a token that will grow with you, for an entire year. Changing and morphing over time to eventually reach its equilibrium.

It is a token where I try to symbolize the journey of life.
Where looking back is the best way to look forward.
Where looking into the future is not a possibility.
Where each day is as uncertain as the next.

A token that will surprise you and have its ups and downs as it grows over time.



Pricing:
Dutch auction 64-16-8, where anybody that picks one up at 64 tez gets a print of how their galaxy looks on any day from the present to day 0. Meaning you can claim the print at any point in the future.

The print will be printed on high quality hahnemühle torchon paper at 30x40 cm (11.81 x 15.75 in). Printed at a local print shop here in Utrecht. This paper has a rough texture to it that matches the textures of space perfectly.



Usage:
- Hover over your Asterium to view the name, date, days passed, status and render stats.
- Double press to export the current frame as a .png image.
- Use the slider at the bottom to scroll back in time to the days before today, you can go as far back as day 0 and as far forwards as today.
- The token refreshes every hour, so framing it in a digital picture frame is totally possible!

metadata.name: Punktwelt #107
metadata.description:
Continuing on the theme of color perception in Farbteiler, Punktwelt is an exploration of color interaction, projection and perceived depth, and the aesthetics of simple Boolean operations on form.

Each shape is the result of a single block, a rectangular cuboid, subjected to a series of Boolean subtractions with other blocks, and rendered in parallel projection, oblique or axonometric, in the abstract landscape of the Punktwelt.

Some have horizons, some have banded or striped backgrounds. The unnatural drawing order and chromatic differences of the individual faces sometimes yields illusory or paradoxical visual geometries.

Press ’s’ to save a png. Press ’4’ to export a high resolution png. Press ’8’ to export a very high resolution png. Press ’e’ to export an SVG file (may take some time and produce large files).

Aspect ratio variations are 4:5, 5:4, 2:3, 3:2 and 1:1.

Built in Javascript with p5.js, p5.svg and csg.js.

metadata.name: A Day To Remember #84
metadata.description:

metadata.name: Limelight #116
metadata.description:
Inspired by repetitions, symmetry, and evolution in nature, Limelight is a series of moving structures symbolic of natural forms, that emphasize relationships between architectures, transport networks, and materials - all in thirst for light.

Tap anywhere on the artwork or press the space bar to start and stop the animation.

Created with GLSL and p5js. It is fully responsive to any screen size.

To all collectors, reach out on Twitter (@uditmahajan24) if you want a high-resolution image of your mint.

metadata.name: Paper Cut #128
metadata.description:
Paper Cut is a p5.js layered collage composition of Truchet patterns on textured paper. 

For a description of how it was created please see my first ever fxhash article of the same name.

Use the 'r' key on the keyboard to randomise some parameters while keeping the essence of the piece the same. 

Use keys, 2, 3 and 4 to render at higher resolutions.

attributes.name: Pattern Variations
attributes.value: All Hexagons, Squares with No Straight Lines, All Triangles
